\viewkind4\uc1\pard\keepn\s1\sa60\qc\lang2057\kerning28\b\f0\fs32 Infoscape - a radical new way of accessing and \line utilising complex information in the arts\par
\pard\keepn\s3\sb60\sa60\qc\kerning0\f1\fs22 Author: David Everitt   Date: 25.10.01\par
\pard\keepn\s2\sb120\sa60\f0 Summary\par
\pard\b0\f1 A proposal for the research and development of a system allowing users to gain valuable insights from complex sets of data. A user-matched 'data landscape' will evoke the navigation and foraging skills inherent in actual human life through a 'landscape' metaphor as a front end to large bodies of data. The aim is to enable satisfactory information retrieval, comparison and evaluation at far shorter times than the traditional 'desktop' computer interface allows.\par
\pard\fi284 The development of a generic model will follow a specific application of this idea to the mapping of disability arts activity and audiences in the East midlands region. The region is of specific interest because it has no central city and ,as yet, no comprehensive body of qualitative and/or quantitative data in this special interest area.\par
The system plans to cover cultural, ethnic, financial, geographical, temporal, or other details as specified by users, such that one or more data sets can be searched, isolated, filtered and compared from multiple perspectives.\par
\pard\keepn\s1\sb240\sa60\kerning28\b\f0\fs28 1. General information\par
\pard\keepn\s2\sb120\sa60\kerning0\fs22 1.1 Background\par
\pard\b0\f1 Recent Disability Advisory Group (DAG) research identified mapping as one of the action research areas to be tackled in order to formulate a coherent strategy:\par
\pard\li284\ri227\sb120\sa60\fs20 'A key area for strategic development would be to create a mapping structure which identifies provision, identifies needs, and identifies where a mismatch between these creates a gap in provision [\'85] the group recommends  that this idea is allowed to continue forward to create a recognisable and comprehensive resource within which future strategic developments can be situated.'\par
\pard\fs22 The original DAG idea included a physical public artwork as an interface to data held digitally. After further research by T\'e2n Draig and David Everitt, taking into account the vigorous interest expressed by potential end-users in a computer-based system, the public artwork is now seen as a separate project to be funded separately as an artist's commission once the data system is useable.\par
\pard\fi284 Due to the innovative nature of the proposal (via Dave Everitt's role as visiting researcher in art and technology) Loughborough University of Technology Computer-Human Interaction department (LUTCHI; within Computer Science) has expressed an interest in: becoming a formal development partner with EMA; advising on partnership match funding through computer science research sources; and providing a research and development environment and contacts within which the project can be realised. A formal letter is in preparation.\par
Presentations of a web page with clickable images demonstrating the basic idea behind the system have been made to interested parties including the ACE R&D Directorate:\par
\pard\li284\ri227\sb120\sa60\fs20 http://creative.lboro.ac.uk/gof/wip/ifs/\par
\pard\keepn\s2\sb120\sa60\b\f0\fs22 1.2 Timescale\par
\pard\b0\f1 Current plans are for a three-stage project (details of these stages can be provided on demand) with a specific arts and disability remit to the first and part of the second stages:\par
\pard{\pntext\f1 1.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf1\pnindent360\pnstart1\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\fi-357\li357\sb120\tx360 essential disability arts and audiences data gathering based on user specifications, with special attention to the quality and type of data required. Qualitative, personal data will be gathered as well as statistical data. The result will be an East-Midlands specific disability arts mapping system as a prototype for the more comprehensive and flexible system of the successive stages.\line Time: 12-18 months. Funding range: \'a320-\'a330,000\par
{\pntext\f1 2.\tab}Following useability studies, the development of a more extensive version allowing registered users to add new data, with public access to relevant information; testing of other arts mapping data on the system. \line Time: 10-14 months. Funding range: \'a325-\'a332,000\par
{\pntext\f1 3.\tab}The expansion of the existing system into a generic one into which many different kinds of arts (and other) data could be mapped. \line Time: 10-14 months. Funding range: \'a325-\'a332,000\par
\pard\keepn\s2\sb120\sa60\b\f0 1.3 The quality of the data is paramount\par
\pard\b0\f1 Quality control throughout data gathering is essential to the success of the entire project. For instance, information on arts and disability already held by an organisation may not cover details that might emerge in interviews by trained disabled arts workers with a knowledge of the region's activities. For the disability-specific stage, the aim will be to get to the heart of where, how and why disabled people apply for funding, run projects, work as artists and arts workers, and make up audiences. It is essential that this process is perceived as being entirely neutral, and that qualitative data in the form of quotations and personal accounts makes up much of the material.\par
\pard\fi284 The other main data-gathering task will be to assess the quality of extant information to identify deficiencies. Interviews with potential users will determine exactly what kinds of data will be most useful. Also, assessing existing data categories used in the arts will:\par
\pard\li284\ri227\sb120\sa60\fs20 'ensure that the classifications and categories used in research are consistent with those used across government departments and, where possible, throughout Europe' \super 5\nosupersub\par
\pard\fs22 The outcome will be a basic structure of 'must have' items as core data.\par
