It is envisaged that \b strategic \b0 needs will be to supplement or even underpin disability and other arts strategies, to evaluate provision and need, and to identify areas requiring attention. 'What if' scenarios are also likely. Difficulties the system aims to solve are the sifting of essential information from vast amounts of complex data, and the maintenance of that data by multiple users and interest groups.\par
\par
Arts\b  providers \b0 are likely to use the system to discover where (as \b arts creators\b0 ) hubs and voids of activity exist. As \b arts hosts \b0 they may want to focus new developments and encourage new audience participation where cultural or geographical attendance gaps exist, or to maximise on existing 'constellations' of activity. The avoidance of clashing schedules, and the sharing of information concerning the programming of events is also a likely use.\par
\par
Arts\b  users\b0  and audiences may see the system as a kind of 'what's on' resource (a public-access version could become a satellite project). One immediate use would be to provide access to the kind of information people need to intelligently develop arts participation in their own area, or to invite contributions to the map from smaller 'home-grown' arts activities. The inclusion of rural areas and smaller towns alongside other regional information has obvious benefits.\par
\pard\keepn\s1\sb240\sa60\kerning28\b\f0\fs28 2 Technical details\par
\pard\keepn\s2\sb120\sa60\kerning0\fs22 2.1 3D information mapping (see web page for illustrations)\par
\pard\li284\ri227\sb120\sa60\b0\f1\fs20 'Information visualisation can be defined as the visualisation and navigation of abstract data structures.'\super  1\nosupersub\par
\pard\fs22 3D information visualisation allows the user to intuitively navigate, grasp and clarify threads in complex data through spatial metaphors. These emerging systems handle the increasing complexity of data, taking over where conventional databases fail \super 2\nosupersub . They are a current 'hot' area in computer interface research. The web page illustrations are provided as a simple guide to one possible appearance of the system, but final appearance will depend on user requirements. The rapidly-dominant XML for information handling, linked to VRML for display, are the technologies most suitable at present.\par
\pard\keepn\s2\sb120\sa60\b\f0 2.2 Dynamic updateablity\par
\pard\b0\f1 The intention is to make the system dynamically updateable. Contributors may enter new data remotely via standard text-based forms on a website and quickly see the result \super 3\nosupersub . This updating could be:\par
\pard\li720\sb120 1. \b local\b0 : on the user's machine - i.e. they would be able to update the data and change how it is displayed without uploading new data via the web. This might be useful for experimenting with 'what if' scenarios, and would be faster than the web at present;\par
2. \b remote\b0 : via the web or an organisation's intranet. Updates to the data would either need to be uploaded to a server or communicated directly between online users so that one data set is common to all. For security a password system would be used for data entry and modification.\par
\pard\keepn\s2\sb120\sa60\b\f0 2.3 Audio-navigation\par
\pard\b0\f1 The incorporation of sound as a navigation device will also be investigated, since the primacy of vision should never be assumed. Besides, sound can be a more intuitive and perhaps subtler guide to complex information. For instance, density of activity could be represented by a similar sonic density, either in the speed of separate notes representing connections to each node, or in pitch, or in a number of other ways. Visually impaired users will be inform useability tests and specific user feedback processes.\par
